A better year for migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the migration crisis in the Mediterranean.
First, Europe and the international community are applying a cruelly unsuitable system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants.
Secondly, in the face of the inefficiency of this system, populist actors keep exploiting fears to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies whose construction required some 70 years of relentless efforts.
This is why it is essential that this year a truly active approach be undertaken at both European and global levels.
In September next, UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit aimed at building a strong global system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants and refugees.
We hope that states will be ready to commit concretely and durably.
This necessary commitment was severely lacking during the year 2015.
In fact, the international community would have been able to limit the severity of last year's crisis if it had provided even the most modest support to frontline countries – Turkey, Lebanon and Jordan – which together host no less than four million refugees.
With approximately 10 billion €, these countries would have been better able to house, feed and provide education to refugees, thus reducing the temptation to flee to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany up to 21 billion € every year in the coming years.
But the financial implications of the crisis are on a completely different scale than its human and political cost.
Over a million people risked their lives last year by crossing the Mediterranean, enduring a exhausting journey through the Balkans afterwards.
Nearly 4,000 migrants lost their lives there, while many European countries turned their backs on the survivors by refusing to grant them asylum.
The most cynical political actors have mercilessly exploited citizens' fears, promoting an odious nationalist vision that either ignores or distorts the lived experiences of migrants.
In the United States, for example, not a single one of the 780,000 refugees settled since September 11, 2001, has been found guilty of terrorist acts.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more taxes than they receive in social benefits.
Yet, extremist parties are dangerously flirting with taking political power in some European countries, and are currently gaining support even within formerly liberal strongholds.
Anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success is also leading traditional parties to promote hostile immigration policies themselves.
This situation has seriously undermined European cooperation.
The EU program aimed at dealing with the million refugees arriving on its shores only managed to « relocate » 190.
Border controls in six countries belonging to the Schengen area have been reinstated, at least temporarily.
In the eyes of the rest of the world, the EU now appears chauvinist and incompetent.
Of course, resolving this crisis is not only about Europe; responsibility cannot be defined by mere geographical proximity.
Whatever the case, the EU is likely facing a threat to its own existence today, which it can overcome only if it demonstrates firmly the solidarity and international leadership it is capable of.
That is why it is up to the member states to take the initiative by proposing solutions.
The most urgent priority is to establish legal and secure pathways allowing refugees to reach Europe.
This does not mean asserting that every migrant in difficulty must be welcomed.
Nonetheless, it is incumbent upon the EU to be more systematically generous in determining the number of refugees to welcome, and to employ ordered mechanisms aimed at facilitating their entry.
A system like this would allow protecting migrants while preserving Europe (through the possibility of thoroughly examining applications).
Beyond a démarche aimed at deterring asylum seekers from risking their lives by crossing the Mediterranean, such an approach would allow projecting an image of solidarity towards frontline countries, which continue to host the majority of refugees.
An equally important aspect, this approach would encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to the efforts.
This leads us to the second priority of 2016: building a solid global system for protecting vulnerable refugees and migrants.
This objective will above all require more countries to accept hosting refugees.
In recent years, the United Nations Refugee Agency has only managed to resettle less than 75 000 of the approximately 20 million refugees annually.
Millions of them end up in a situation of prolonged migration, with an average duration estimated at 25 years, prisoners of a sort of purgatory and uncertain about the day of a potential return to their country.
In 2016, it is necessary that developed countries agree to welcome a cumulative number of nearly one million refugees each year, either through their resettlement or by granting them a humanitarian, student, professional, or other visa.
Canada having stated that it would welcome 50 000 Syrian refugees this year, this is a clearly achievable goal.
At the same time, the international community must support the integration of refugees in major host countries such as Turkey, Kenya, Lebanon, and Jordan.
In the current state of affairs, these countries receive only a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually needed per refugee for purposes of housing, food, care, education, and vocational training during the first years of settlement.
And these figures do not take into account the necessary cost of building or upgrading infrastructure.
In Lebanon, for example, water supply systems are suffering from the pressure caused by the massive arrival of refugees.
In exchange for financing, these host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor markets, and civic institutions.
But effective integration of migrants will only be possible if the countries of Europe and elsewhere rid themselves of their prejudices regarding migrants.
If these groups remain seen as a burden, or even as a threat to security, reactionary political forces will continue to gain ground, depriving newcomers of opportunities and turning fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
On the contrary, if host countries manage to integrate migrants enthusiastically, everyone will benefit – including these countries (notably through inflows of money).
Last month, in Paris, the international community proved that it was capable of subordinating its national interests to a broader global objective: the fight against climate change.
In 2016, it is necessary that a similar effort aims at building a better system for protecting migrants.
This is a matter of life or death for some 20 million refugees, for several million other vulnerable migrants – as well as a profound test of the civic health of democratic societies around the world.
